item.title: Where is the runescape cheating?
item.dc:creator: @Nerice Nerice
item.description:
@Nerice wrote:

Had a long post but removed it.

Its useless, since people come here wanting to learn simple java and have thier hands held, or just to download something that works.

There are other and better places to learn java than here. Here it should be about the client, and bytecode questions should be referred to google. Its different with specific questions, but then all thier questions are wound up being posted here.

Also its actually alot easier when the actual “byte” code and how the JVM itself is interpreting the data is known. Its just as easy to learn those as it is to learn to use BCEL etc… but there is a much better understanding of what is happening if they bothered to learn more advanced (wrong word actually, as its more basic than basic java) java and makes understanding alot of the stupid stuff they do in the client to try to ob stuff alot clearer when its known what the JVM is actually doing with it. Yet people tend to be people, and want what seems to be a easier way out of something, even if its really not, its just the perception.

hell, I would actually be surprised if more than one person can tell me the bytecode instruction the JVM uses for for say… JSR (which is used ALOT in very heavy obfuscation which the RS client is obbed, but not high very high levels)?

item.title: Where is the runescape cheating?
item.dc:creator: @yakman yakman
item.description:
@yakman wrote:

i defiantly agree we should do something about it, I’m thinking some tutorials, not copy/paste ones, but ones that tell you how it works and all that.
like, “Before you start editing, the client tries to connect to localhost, you have to edit it to connect to the real RS2 servers, do to this, look in main() for…”

when i first started client hacking, it was from tutorials on rs-resources main page by taios, there was a short one about how to get it to connect, and a longer one about (the late) hp above heads.
we should make sure these tutorials don’t give too much away about the client, because whenever you put it into words, there is so much information lost, its much better to have people learn it for themselves.

perhaps a sticky in the client hacking section called something like, “So you want to do RS2 Client Hacking?”, which tells you about using old aryan deobs, some things like getting it to connect, and changing strings like “Walk Here” into “Jump Here”. And in all this, constantly go on about “client hacking is common sence” and “jump in and get your hands dirty”.

New people are really good for us, normally the old knowledgeable people aren’t interested in autoing, or learning new things, but new naive people are, and the smart ones will be able to do it.
